":"1057","1189":"1189","1100":"1100","1109":"1109","about 1130":"circa 1130","Thame, Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England","Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England":"Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England"},"en":{"1090–":"1090–Deceased","1082–Male":"1082–Deceased","1090–1150":"1090–1150","1090–Female":"1090–Deceased","1100–Female":"1100–Deceased","–1100":"–1100","1083–1142":"1083–1142","1085–Male":"1085–Deceased","1130–1189":"1130–1189","1130–Male":"1130–Deceased","1109–1147":"1109–1147","1032–1102":"1032–1102","1057–1135":"1057–1135","1090":"1090","about 1080":"about 1080","1032":"1032","1142":"1142","1130":"1130","1085":"1085","1150":"1150","1083":"1083","1082":"1082","1147":"1147","1135":"1135","1102":"1102","1057":"1057","1189":"1189","1100":"1100","1109":"1109","about 1130":"about 1130","Thame, Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England":"Kilkhampton, Cornwall, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Giffard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: (i) relationship name from the Continental Germanic personal name  <i>Gifard</i>. (ii) nickname, perhaps sometimes from Old French  <i>giffard</i> ‘chubby-cheeked, bloated’."],"variants":[{"name":"Jeffords","meanings":["English: variant of   Gifford  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Jefford","meanings":["English:  see  Giffard  ."]},{"name":"Guiver","meanings":["English: (i) nickname, apparently from Middle English  <i>giver</i> ‘giver, donor, bestower’. (ii) variant of   Giffard   with voicing of /f/ to /v/ and loss of final  <i>-d</i>."]},{"name":"Gafford","meanings":["English (southeastern): assimilated form of <b>Gatford</b>, a name of various origins. In Sussex and Surrey it is perhaps a variant of the habitational name <b>Catford</b> from a place so called in Somerset. <b>Gatford</b> is also from the habitational names Gateford (in Worksop, Nottinghamshire) or Gateforth (near Selby, Yorkshire), both formed with Old English <i>gāt</i> ‘goat’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’, influenced by Old Norse <i>geit</i> ‘goat’.","Probably also an altered form of German <b>Gaffert</b>: habitational name from Gaffert near Köslin, Brandenburg, or from a personal name formed with Middle High German <i>gate</i> ‘fellow, companion’. The surname <i>Gaffert</i> is very rare in Germany.","English: perhaps an altered form of   Gatewood  , an occupational name for a ‘goatherd’ (Middle English <i>gate-werde</i>, Old English <i>gātweard</i>) or for a ‘gate keeper’ (Middle English <i>gateward</i>, Old English <i>ʒeatweard</i>, dialect <i>gātward</i>)."]},{"name":"Gifford","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of <b>Giffard</b>, either from the Middle English personal name <i>Gifard</i>, derived from an Old French name of this form deriving from ancient Germanic <i>geb-</i> ‘give, gift’ + <i>hard-</i> ‘hardy, brave’, or perhaps sometimes a nickname from Old French <i>gif(f)ard</i> ‘chubby-cheeked, bloated’."]},{"name":"Jefferd","meanings":["English:  see  Giffard  ."]}]},{"name":"Isabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which 